Procedure: COLPOSCOPY


You and your doctor are considering a test called Colposcopy. This is a type of examination in which the doctor looks through a microscope to examine the patient's cervix. The cervix is part of the womb so the doctor must direct a light into the patient's private area or vagina. The purpose of the test is to make sure that no early type of cancer of the cervix is present. If the doctor sees any area of the cervix that is suspicious, he will take a biopsy or a specimen of the tissue and have it examined further. This colposcopy test is not treatment for any disease; it is just an examination.

Although the patient is placed in an awkward position for the colposcopy test, usually very little or no discomfort or pain is felt. If there is any cramping pain, it generally subsides rapidly.

This test is quite safe and complications from it are very unlikely. Bleeding and infection are uncommon complications of colposcopy when a biopsy is taken. In very rare cases, bleeding and infection from the test have resulted in the need for surgery. Very, very rarely the complications of this test can result in sterility or the inability to bear or have children (if the patient is of childbearing age). Allergic or other bad reaction to one of the substances used in the test is a very uncommon complication. In very, very rare instances, allergic reactions have caused death.

The colposcopy test is a reasonably safe and accurate method of diagnosing cancer of the cervix in the early stages. There may be alternatives to colposcopy available to you, such as various biopsy procedures. These alternatives carry their own risks of complication and have a varying degree of success. Therefore, in those women in which the test is indicated, colposcopy may provide the best chance of successful diagnosis and the lowest risk of complications.
